cluster-0, es-cluster-1, es-cluster-2), I should either remove the `node.name` setting entirely to let Elasticsearch auto-generate it, or find another way to set it dynamically.\n\nThe challenge is that the configmap is shared across all pods, so I can't hardcode different node names for each pod without using environment variable substitution in the pod's entrypoint or an init container—but that would require modifying the StatefulSet itself.\n\nThe simpler fix is to remove the `node.name` setting entirely from the configmap and let Elasticsearch auto-generate node names. Since the cluster is already bootstrapped, the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting only matters during initial formation, not when nodes rejoin, so the mismatch between auto-generated names and the initial master nodes list won't break anything.\n\nHowever, if `node.name` is left blank in the configmap, Elasticsearch will throw a parse error, so I need to either remove the key completely or set it to a valid value—which brings me back to needing dynamic substitution. remove the `node.name` setting from the configmap and let Elasticsearch derive it from the hostname, which should be the pod name in a StatefulSet. Then I can delete the problematic pod to trigger a restart with the corrected configuration. If I remove `node.name` entirely, Elasticsearch will generate a default name from the node ID, which for a fresh pod without persistent data would be random and different from `es-cluster-2`. However, since the cluster is already bootstrapped with es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1 running, the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting only applies during initial bootstrap—a new node joining an existing cluster doesn't need to match that configuration.\n\nThe actual fix is to remove the hardcoded `node.name` from the configmap and correct the `discovery.seed_hosts` to use the proper namespace, then restart the es-cluster-2 pod. In Kubernetes StatefulSets, the pod hostname matches the pod name, and Elast